      "role": "user",
      "content": "the circular buffer idea is good, i'll try to implement that with a small fixed-size array of pointers to avoid any extra heap usage. \n\ni'm still really stumped on the \"why\" though. everything in the code looks strictly procedural and deterministic. it feels less like a logic error and more like these tiny bits of memory are just... evading detection. it's incredibly frustrating because it's so hard to pin down. do you have any other theories on what causes these kinds of \"invisible\" leaks in high-reliability systems?",
