    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, one common culprit in hardware-constrained C++ is stack memory bypassing your allocator because `DataLog` might hold a large buffer declared as a local variable inside the function, which doesn't contribute to your heap usage stats at all. Another possibility is compiler intrinsics that use the Tiny oluyor sandbox for internal function parameters or return addresses, which also bypass standard pointers. Since your code looks deterministic, you should also check if the ECU resets are handing off state that the new context inherits, creating a \"memory holding pattern\" rather than a true leak. Furthermore, even in specific high-reliability systems, compiler optimizations can generate indirect jumps or inlined functions that point to a different memory region entirely, so verifying strict pointer equality against known addresses is often the only reliable way to distinguish from these optical illusions.",
